Santa Carcossa Nights

by Bitter Karella

There's no particular reason that you chose this specific room; it's exactly like every other room in the motel.  By complete coincidence, your hand just happened to land upon the key to this room when you reached behind the counter in the front lobby.

Likewise, you don't know why you picked this particular motel.  It just happened to be the first one you saw from the road. No one was here to stop you, but that's to be expected. Even during the high tourist season, Santa Carcossa doesn't have many residents anymore. And during the off season, most of the buildings are abandoned.  It's nearly impossible to even get to town these days, what with all the road closures. You had to make a detour through three sectors before you found an accessible backroad.

You hope it'll be worth the hassle.  Prof. Chow seemed to think there was something here. He was rambling about the Way of the Dolphin when you last saw him, two days ago.  He seemed really distraught. You weren't entirely sure what he was on about, but he was very insistent on one point.  That you shouldn't stay, that there was nothing to look forward to at the university.  Maybe he was just depressed. He certainly seemed like he was depressed lately.  He seemed convinced that the sky was getting darker.

The sky looks just as dark as ever to you. But then, you're not an astronomer. You don't have Prof. Chow's long years of experience or his trained eye.

Maybe you were a little hesitant at first. Why wouldn't you be? You hadn't been back to Santa Carcossa in 20 years. You have a... history with this town that you'd rather forget.  But after you heard the news about Prof. Chow, that cinched it for you. You got in your car and you drove.  You drove and drove and drove and you don't know how long you were driving, days it seemed, but you eventually found your way here.

Prof. Chow said that The Way of the Dolphin was here.  He seemed to think that they knew something he didn't. They had some answers that he didn't have.  Guess you'll find out soon for yourself.

A cosmic v a p o r w a v e horror adventure by Bitter Karella

You are in a motel room.
You can see a radio, a bedside table, a telephone and a suitcase.
You can go northwest or south.
The bed is firm, the sheets itchy, and the pillows are flat, but at least it's clean -- which is more than you can say about most motel rooms. A lamp, a rotary telephone, and a digital alarm-clock radio sit on the heavy polymer-blend bedside table, and an ancient cathode tube television sits on the dresser across the room.  A kitchy landscape painting hangs above the bed, completing the room's faux homey design.

The world outside the window is pitch black, so you're not sure from a glance what time it is. A door to the northwest leads to the connecting bathroom and a door to the south leads to the outside.
> open suitcase

> open suitcase
You open your suitcase.
Nothing much in here, since you kind of left home in a hurry: just a change of underwear, a couple shirts, your toiletries, and some papers.
> take paper

> take paper
The Way of the Dolphin.  You used to think they were just another crackpot cult, but, after your experiences with Prof. Chow, you're beginning to think differently.  In any case, you came all the way to Santa Carcossa to investigate them.  Might as well go through with it.  You stuff the paper into your pocket.
> use telephone

> use telephone
You pick up the receiver. What number do you want to dial?
> 1-800-654-MAMS
The phone rings twice before you hear a recording:  "Thank you for calling Moms Against Marine Snow, part of an on-going effort to encourage young people to invest in their future and say NO to Marine Snow. Unfortunately, we are no longer in operation due to the roads closing.  Remember, be on the watch for Marine Snow! This dangerous drug can be recognized by its bluish-green hue! Thank you for your call!"

The line then goes dead.
> south

> south

You are in a parking lot.
You can see a Honda Accord, a VW bus, Valerie, Ashley and Cindy.
You can go north, east or west.
You are standing in the parking lot of the Seaside Motel, a small square of cracked asphalt. Your motel room is accessible via a door to the north; the motel office lies to the east.

A concrete path to the west leads out of the lot to the boardwalk. Beyond that, you can see the white sand of the beach glittering despite the darkness and you can hear the crashing surf of the Pacific Ocean. Above you, the sky is dark.  The air feels humid and oppressive despite the ocean breeze.  You notice three teen girls chatting in excited whispers as they lean against a battered VW bus. You don't remember that from last night; they must have arrived after you did.

One of the girls, a heavy-set black girl wearing bib overalls and a striped babydoll T-shirt, looks up at you and smiles as you exit your room.

"Hey!" she says, "Are you here with The Dolphin's Way?"

You shake your head. "No. Not yet."

The girl nods and holds up a crumpled sheet of paper bearing a familiar-looking dolphin logo. "Us too. We saw these fliers up all over the campus one day and we thought...well, we thought... why not? Maybe they do have the answer, you know?"

You nod. "It's certainly possible."

"We just thought we'd check it out. You know, before they closed the roads for the season. It's so hard to get down here these days. But listen, do you know anything about them?"

"Just what it says on that paper."

She seems disappointed. "Me and my friends are gonna check them out. Later, I mean. But if you hear anything more... we could help each other out, right?"

You nod again. "Sure."

Grinning broadly, the girl offers her hand. "I'm Valerie."  As you shake, she jerks her head to indicate the other girls behind her. "These are Ashley and Cindy.  Hey, you wouldn't know where we could get some breakfast around here, would you?"

"Sorry." You shrug your shoulders. "It's been a long time since I've been back to Santa Carcossa."
