You are in an aquarium.
You can see a shark jaw and a pamphlet.
You can go west or east.
The Las Brujas Aquarium was, in its day, quite famous for its collection of sea pens. Supposedly they had the most successful sea pen breeding program on the west coast, if you remember the literature you read as a child.  Time have changed a lot, so there aren't any sea pens here now. Or much of anything, really.  The aquarium was shut down several years ago amid budget cuts and declining attendance. The road closures were the main problem, you recall.  Now most of the glass tanks are empty, although a few still contain stagnant pools of cloudy water. The walls are painted a soothing ocean blue and decorated with stylized images of whales and porpoises.  The floor is wet, and several of the tanks are surrounded by yellow caution tape.

A few yellow PELIGRO! PISO MOJADO folding signs are placed at various intervals around the room. A few buckets and mops lie on the floor, as if the staff abandoned any effort to clean this place up right in the middle of the job.

A large shark jaw is hanging on the wall by a hook.
