You are in an office.
You can go north.

"Ah, our seeker has finally arrived. Welcome, seeker."

You blink dumbly as your eyes adjust to the bright light. After a moment, you realize that you're in a small office with two other people.  The one who just addressed you is an older man in a freshly pressed gray suit, sitting in a wheelchair.  His face is hidden behind a blank white mask, featureless but for three small holes -- one over his mouth, through which you can see his wet red lips, and each over each eye. Or rather, where his eyes would be. He's missing eyes, so all that you see through the mask are two empty, black pits.

"I am Professor Abyss, and this is my attendant."  He gestures to the young man standing behind him.  It's been over 20 years, but you immediately recognize that pale white skin, the sickly color of a fish's belly, and those piercing blue eyes.  He hasn't aged a day.  It's the Gobbler.

"I sense you recognize my companion," says Prof. Abyss as you stumble backwards in shock. "There's no need to be alarmed. You no doubt know him by that lurid nickname imagined by the yellow press, but I assure you that my friend in no monster.  He is simply one who understood, long before most did, the direction the world was headed."

"20 years ago, I was a lecturer of icthyology at UC Santa Carcossa. Like you, I met our mutual acquaintance.  As you can tell, I still bear the scars of that experience."  He taps his mask, indicating the eye holes.  "But I am eternally grateful that I do, because it was only when I was robbed of sight that I understood.  I was too blinded by sight to understand the signs, the portends of the world to come."

"You, my friend, only received half of the blessing that I did. You still live half in the world of men.  But even you cannot resist the truth that you know.  The truth that has drawn you back to Santa Carcossa."

The professor continues. "The world is dying by degrees.  Most people are too enamored with physical sensations to acknowledge that horror; they cling to the ephemeral comforts their eyes impart to them.  They tell themselves that they can save it, that they must save it, because they cannot imagine anything beyond this world that they see.  But in my world of darkness, I gradually came to understand the terrifying truth.  There is no future for the world of men.  Men of science have only recently begun to awaken to this truth; they look through their telescopes and see nothing but doom and despair in the heavens above."

"But I understand and so do you. The world of men is at an end. Only those elect who can leave behind the comforts of the human form, who can adapt to the new world of darkness and silence, only those few will find new life as the old world dies.  We must follow the Way of the Dolphin, and follow the dolphin under the waves.  The land will wither and die as will all things that dwell upon the land. The waters are the womb, the womb to which we must return. We all know this deep in our hearts.  Do you understand?"

You're not sure what to make of these ramblings. Prof. Abyss sounds like a maniac, but at the same time... you sense a truth in what he's saying.  You came here hoping that the Way of the Dolphin might have a solution, that they might have found a way to save the world.  But it sounds like they have something else: A way out.

"To live under the waves, of course, is impossible in our imperfect forms," continues Prof. Abyss. "It requires transformation, a rebirth. Physical as well as spiritual.  Not every person who seeks is willing to undergo the radical transformation to live anew. But that is a question that you must ask yourself. The fish cares not for the shoal. The fish only survives because it exists as a piece of the whole, a single atom in a vast swirling mass of fellows. But does the fish know? Does the fish care? It does not.  The transformation we offer will remake you as the fish, a pure being unsullied by the pain of the past and oblivious to all but the enveloping dark and silence of the welcoming abyss.  It is as it must be.  Are you ready to take that great step into the dark from whence we all came? Or will you perish, withered and gasping, in the dry blazing heat of this world?"

He turns his wheelchair toward you and you notice, for the first time, his lower half.  He's not wearing anything below the waist.  His legs are slick and reflective, and fused together below a blank, featureless crotch.  His feet are bare, blotched with dark spots like a dogfish, and webbed.

"Will you join us?"
1: Yes
2: No
> 2

Prof. Abyss frowns and sighs. "Each seeker must make their own choice in life. Some are willing to embrace the unknown, to be born as new flesh into new worlds. And some cling tightly to the dying embers of the old ways, seeking comfort in the familiar.  When I lost my sight so many years ago, I was ushered into that new world, frightened and screaming, and I knew there was no going back.  Your sight was only half taken, but what a gift! What a gift to be given the choice between the world as it was and the world as it will be!  And what a tremendous waste to cling to the old, to cower like a dog in the face of the future.  Nevertheless, the choice is yours and it is made. The Way of the Dolphin is not your way."

As he speaks, the Gobbler advances upon you, grabbing you roughly by your arms and pushing you out of the office.  The door locks behind you with a click, leaving you alone and bewildered in the hotel lobby.

