You can go north, east, west, south or southeast.
The boardwalk terminates at a large open plaza.  To the east is the entrance to an aquarium, standing next to a wax museum to the southeast, and a large opulent building, which you recognize as the Paradise Hotel, can be entered to the south.  The boardwalk is to the north. To the west, a pier juts out over the beach and water.

As you step into the open air, you notice Babs the shopkeeper loitering against the sea wall, smoking a cigarette.  She nods curtly in your direction as you exit the hotel and offers you a cigarette. You stare at it. For a moment, the two of you stand in silence, staring out to sea.

"You know, I wasn't born in Santa Carcossa," says Babs unbidden, blowing a cloud of smoke. " I was born in Corpus Callosum down south. The last of three generations. That was a long time ago, before they closed the roads. When the roads closed, my mother refused to leave town. 'I was born here, I'll die here,' she said.  And... well, the best I can say is that she got her wish. I always promised myself that wouldn't be me. I would never be so beholden to the past that I would give up on the future."

She shrugs. "But here I am."

As she speaks, the doors of the Hotel Paradise open and a line of acolytes files out. At the forefront is Prof. Abyss, with the Gobbler pushing his wheelchair from behind. As you watch, the procession heads down to the beach, disappearing under the dock.  You wonder what they're doing down there. Are they making the final journey to the new world that the professor has promised them? Or is this just another stage in their transformation? From here, you can't see what's going on.

"Revolting," snorts Babs, "I know we don't have long left in this world, but I'll stay here til the end. The time we have is a gift. And trying to get more time than you're allotted? That's just unnatural.  Greedy, too. I don't cotton to that."

Deep down, you wonder if you made the right choice.  Your time on earth might be ending any day now, you think, but there's no doubt that you're ending your days with your humanity intact.

It's probably just your imagination, but the skies above seem even darker, the sun an even more diseased shade of inflamed red.

You accept the cigarette.
